      "content": "i've been mapping out some old street layouts in london and nyc lately for a project and i keep hitting these weird geometric overlaps. like, if you overlay the ley lines common in old european cities onto the grid of lower manhattan, there are these specific intersections that just... don't make sense for standard urban planning. they're too precise. do you see any reason why city planners would intentionally align major transit hubs with these non-standard geometric patterns?",
